But during the reading, I have one confusion, let me explain with code as following: 

     export class PageOneComponent {
      subscription: Subscription;
    
      constructor(private demoQuery: DemoQuery) {}
    
      ngOnInit() {
        this.subscription = this.demoQuery.selectSomeProp$.subscribe(prop =&gt; {
          this.someMethod();
        });
      }
    
      someMethod() {}
    }

This example is from this post which is good: https://netbasal.com/why-its-important-to-unsubscribe-from-rxjs-subscription-a7a6455d6a02

And there is memory leak in the above case. Let&#39;s make a small change: 

    export class PageOneComponent {
      subscription: Subscription;
    
      constructor(private demoQuery: DemoQuery) {}
    
      ngOnInit() {
        // change is here, remove the assignment to this.subscription
        this.demoQuery.selectSomeProp$.subscribe(prop =&gt; {
          this.someMethod();
        });
      }
    
      someMethod() {}
    }

In the second case, I remove the assignment part `this.subscription`. I think there is memory leak in the second case as well. &lt;br&gt;

Since the Observable(`this.demoQuery.selectSomeProp$`) is `subscribe`, so the Observable will keep alive and lead to memory leak. Both cases have this issue. &lt;br&gt;

And beside this one, I think the first case have another point leading to memory leak. As the post said `the subscription function holds a reference to this (the component instance) therefore the PageOne instance isnt available for garbage collection and will not be collected.` So the component instance keep alive lead to second point of memory leak. &lt;br&gt;

That&#39;s my understanding. &lt;br&gt; If we want to fix the issue, We can add the following code, which is straight forward and everyone knows it, I guess: 

    ngOnDestroy() {
      this.subscription.unsubscribe();
    }

My further question is how does it indeed fix the two memory leak issues mentioned above? Especially the component level issue. &lt;br&gt; I think from the view point of Javascript Garbage Collection is helpful.

